{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_frederick_ver02/data/sn84024547/00279555776/1958021901/0096.xml":{"full_text":"f\u00bbage S\nMationai Home Offices\nCROATIAN FRATERNAL I N ION\nPittsburgh, Pennsylvania\nTHAT\nTHE Croatian Fraternal Union is\nmuch more than merely interested in\nthe American Croatian Singers Federation\n(ACSF) should come as no surprise.\nComprised of choirs affiliated with its\ntwo component Alliances, \"Faller\" and\n\"Mihanovicthe ACSF came into being in\nGary. Ind., May 30, 1949, with the formal\nadoption of by-laws and the\nelection of leaders to govern\nthe at long last amalgamated\ncultural groups.\nIt was on that historic oc\ncasion that the Croatian Fra\nternal Union first donated\n$500.00 to the fledgling Federation and\npledged it its moral and material support.\nThat promise has been kept inviolate to\nthis date.\nThe Croatian Fraternal Union again\nshowed its faith in the future of the ACSF\nwhen the Delegates to the Society's 9th\nNat'l Quadrennial Convention of 1955 voted\nthe Federation another grant, this time the\namount of $1.000.00.\nCould the ACSF continue to exist with\nout the Croatian Fraternal Union\nNot in our estimation.\nThe last major undertaking of the\nACSF was the staging of its 2nd National\nSinging Festival May 26-27. 1956, in Chi\ncago's famous Orchestra Hall.\nIts next order of business calls for a\nMarch 22-23. 1958, Conference in Javor\nHall. Pittsburgh, of representatives of all\nthe Eastern and Mid-Western groups affi\nliated with the Federation.\nHighlight of the Conference will be a\nBanquet to be held in Javor Hall the eve\nning of Saturday, March 22, an affair which\nshould prove to be one for the books.\nAs always, the Editors of the Zajedni\u010dar\nare ready to come to the publicity aid of the\nFederation in its promotion of the two-day\nConference and the Banquet planned for\nthe occasion.\nIt will be a pleasure to cooperate with\nthe leadership of the ACSF.\nStep Forward\nWE\nHAVE long p\u00abW4eized the varied\nactivities of the Croatian Fraternal\nUnion's Milwaukee-West Allis, Wisconsin,\nMothers Club, at times to the point of edi\ntorial praise.\nNow we feel that the members of the\nClub are in line for another editorial orchid,\nthis time for their undertaking of a wonder\nful new youth project.\nTheir goal: The organization of a\nJunior Tamburi tsa Orchestra.\nIt will, of course, require a great deal\nof cooperation, patience and understanding\nand to get this Milwaukee-West\nAllis cultural project under sail.\nHence the decision of the area's Mothers\nClub to forward letters to Lodges 255,\n261,391. 392,731 and 807 asking for dona\ntions toward the purchase of tamburitza in\nstruments for the youngsters who will one\nday repay their supporters in many and\nlasting ways.\nErgo also the wise decision of this Moth\ners Club to bring in bro. Charles Elias of\nnearby Kenosha. Wise., as the instructor of\nthe juvenile tamburitzans.\nIf there is a more talented tamburitzan\nin North America than bro. Elias is\nthere then it's news to us.\nOne more thing: We hope our elder\nmembers in Milwaukee and West Allis don't\ntry to discourage this youth project on the\ngrounds that \"it just can't be done.\"\nIt has been done, and done in a big way,\nin such Western Pennsylvania CFU centers\nas Farrell, McKeesport, Ambridge, Clairton,\nAliquippa. Trafford, and Pittsburgh. Also\nin Detroit, Mich., Minnesota's Iron Range,\nSo. Chicago, 111., San Francisco, Calif., and\nelsewhere.\nWhy not, then, in the Milwaukee-West\nAllis area? No reason at all!\nv\u00ab A BIT OF PHILOSOPHY\nVO THOSE who talk and talk\nThis adage doth appeal\n\".The steam that blows the whistle\nWill never turn a wheel.\nty.*-\naay\nWEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY 19, 1958\nACSF Conclave More Orchids\nENGLISH SECTION\nEstablished November 6, 1929. Published weekly\nBy The\nCroatian Fraternal Union Of America\nSTEPHEN F. BRKICH, English Editor\nEditorial Offices. 3441 Ker be* Street. MMsbirgb IS, fl.\nTelephones: ML'seum 2-4470 2-4471\nIniolirllrd artlrle*. manii\u00abcrlptii. Intter*. ptetirei. \u00abte.,\nsubmitted to THE 7AJEDNICAB ar* forward\u00ab\u00ab! at the\nowner'\u00ab risk and TRK ZAJEDNI\u010cAR eipreMlj dealea\nhit rr spoasihilitT for their nafekreping or retvrn. TBF.\nZAJI'UMCAB reaerre\u00ab the ritht\nto\nSUPREME\nSupervision\nedit. reri\u00bbe or rtjMl\nartitla or otker matter fabmltted far piktletnn.\nANOTHER\nCFU center deserving of edi\u00ad\ntorial praise is Southern California,\nwhere our members operate from a Central\nCommittee which is never at a loss for\nsomething worthwhile to undertake.\nTo cite but one example.\nAt a recent meeting, the Committee ap\npointed a Ways and Means Committee to\nwork out a program designed to imbue the\nyounger members with pride in their heri\ntage and a thorough understanding of the\nCroatian Fraternal Union's meaning to our\npeople in the United States of America, Ca\nnada. and the Territory of Alaska.\nA large order, to be sure. But not an\nimpossible task by any means.\nInteresting to note is that bro. Milan\nKirin is at the head of this Southern Cali\nfornia youth movement.\nInteresting because bro. Kirin, for years\na member of the Society's High Trial\nBoards of the past, is one of those \"ageless\nwonders\" who never tires of working with\nyounger people who show sincere interest\nin the Society.\nInteresting also because this represents\na challenge to a man who and he will be\nthe first to admit it should have been put\nout to pasture annums ago in return for\nhis many years of work in behalf of the\nCroatian Fraternal Union and its members\nin his area.\nIf our younger members in Southern\nCalifornia will but follow the fraternal ad\nvice of bro. Kirin and his Central Committee\nassociates, men and women devoted to the\nSociety, they will be the better off later in\nlife.\nAnd now forward!\nDid Their Share\ni\nPRES. bro. V. I. Mandich is\ncompleting today on page seven his two\npart treatise dealing with the 1957 statisti\ncal analysis of the Society.\nSince he has Canada under study, we\nrecommend that our members in the Do\nminion take a good look at what they did\nlast year for the welfare and betterment\nof the Croatian Fraternal Union via the\n1957 Membership Campaign which the\nHome Office dedicated in thier honor.\nThey did very well. So well that we doff\nour hat in open admiration.\nAs bro. Mandich points out, our Ca\nnadian Field Workers were responsible in\n1057 for one-third of the new members and\n\u00a9ue-fourth of the new insurance which be\nfell the Croatian Fraternal Union during its\nMembership Campaign of last year.\nConsidering everything with empha\nsis on the numerical difference between our\nUSA and Canadian Field Workers our\nmembers across the border may well be\nproud of this work record.\nTrue, our members in Canada are closer\nto the CFU than are their brethren down in\nthe \"bustling\" United States.\nAnd there are good reasons for this pe\nculiar Canadian CFU affinity.\nThe best of reasons.\nLike the feeling that our people in Can\nada really need the Society.\nBut we still think that they deserve rec\nognition for what they did during the Mem\nbership Campaign of 1957 even though\nsome will say \"So what, they didn't work\nafield for nothing.\"\nKapa vam dolje!\nIn Passing\nThis\nis no mere busi\nness \"decline\" the\no u n y i s o i n\nthrough, though that's\nwhat President Eisen\nhower's Economic Re\u00ad\nport calls it. It's a real depression. Five of\nthe country's best known economists so\ntestify, at any rate. Furthermore all five\nagree that the country will not be out of\nthis depression by next November's elec\ntions, as predicted by Secretary of Com\nmerce Sinclair Weeks. While all five ex\nperts agreed on where the country's econo\nmy is now and will be for the next 10\nmonths, they were by no means agreed on\nwhat should be done to snap out of it.\nPeter Edson, Pittsburgh \"Press\"\n\"ZAJEDNI\u010cAR\"\nJunior Jottings\nMichiel \u00abrasha\nJunior Order Director\nThough most of the of\nficial correspondence between\nthe CFU headquarters and\nthe membership is done\nthrough the intermediary\nthe lodge secretary or nest\nmanager there are occa\nsions wherein the member\nfinds it necessary to write di\nrectly.\nThere is nothing wrong\nwith this except that the very\n[purpose expediency is\nI defeated by the failure of the\nwriter in many cases to prop\nerly identify himself,\nIt must be remembered that\nyour Croatian Fraternal Uni\non is a huge organization with\nclose to 110,000 members re\nsiding across the length and\nbreadth of this vast continent.\nI A name, by itself, therefore\nusually is not enough too i\ndentify you and time has to\nbe lost in further letter ex\nchanges asking for your lodge\nor nest and certificate num\nbers.\nKeep in mind that to as\nsure prompt and adequate re\nsponse to your inquiry you\nshould supply headquarters\nwith all this data.\n1\nThe Society has countless\nmembers with similar, yes,\neven with identical names. In\nsuch cases only your certifi\ncate number will establish\npositive identity.\nChange Of Surname\nAnother and very serious\ndeterrent to expediency and\nproper identification is the\nfailure of female members to\nfile a change of surname upon\nmarriage. A letter from such\nwill carry their married name\nwhile our records here still\ncarry the maiden name.\nThis neglect is the cause of\nmuch delay and misunder\nstanding in the request for a\nyear's pre-paid dues which ac\ncompanies a Term applica\ntion. The mother, or nest\nmanager, uses the married\nname in completing the pre\npaid dues request while our\nrecords still carry that moth\ner under her maiden name.\nNeedless to say much time\nand at least two letters are\nneeded to establish identity\nand eligibility for the award.\nThe same holds true in the\ncase of the $20 pre-paid dues\ncoming to a youngster who\nis enrolled on a permanent\n(Jr. Jottings P. 10)\nDetroit Koio Classes\nWill Resume Feb. 20th\nDETROIT The Mothers\nClub of CFU Nest 318 will re\nsume their children's kolo\nclasses Thursday, February\n20, at 7:00 p.m. in the Croa\ntian Hall, located at 1735 Mc\nNichols Road.\nOur two capable and pa\ntient teachers will be Nata\nlie Babich and Martha Las\nlovic.\nSo parents, please bring the\nchildren. Help them to take\nadvantage of this wonderful\nopportunity to learn the tra\nditional kolos and I am sure\nthey will be forever grateful\nto you.\n77lis\nName Means Little\nThe Society is made up\nof some 600 senior units or\nlodges plus 500 juvenile affi\nliates called nests. Thus even\nlodge officers and nest man\nagers should furnish adequate\ninformation as to their unit\naffiliation, especially so if\nthey are not using formal let\nterheads which would help i\ndentify them.\nNone of the above is inten\nded as criticism, but merely\nas an attempt to expedite cor\nrespondence and desired ac\ntion.\nWe here at headquarters\nwant to be of service but we\ncan serve only when we know\nthe identity of the one who\nseeks that servicc. Remember\nthat when a letter arrives\nhere with only your name it\nmeans little or nothing unless\nthat letter provides us also\nwith your lodge or nest and\ncertificate numbers.\nHAAustralianc\nAnne Majetic, Pub.\nHe Hobnobs With Prince and Peasant Alike VI\nis the autobiography of\nZlatko Balokovic. international\nly famed violinist, a man uni\nversal by choice as well as by\nchance, and a member of Lodge\n326 of the Croatian Fraternal\nUnion of America.\nV I N o e e y\nand New Zea\u00ad\nland concert tour, we headed\nnorth in 1931 through the ma\ngical region of the Great\nBarrier Reef whose coral is\nlands extend for 1,200 miles\nalong the northeasterly coast\nof Australia.\nEach evening up to 100,000\npigeons fly from the Aus\ntralian mainland to these is\nlands hundreds of giant tur\ntles live on the sandy beach\nes and numerous white cock\natoos are found in that para\ndise of flora and fauna.\nOn Christmas Day of\nthat year we arrived at one\nof the most isolated is\nlands \"Thursday Island.\"\nSince it is very near the\nEquator, the heat and\ndampness were almost un\nbearable and we thought\nwith nostalgia of a snowy\nChristmas.\nFrom there we sailed to\nward what is perhaps the\nmost interesting island in the\nworld, Bali, often called \"The\nLast Paradise.\"\nShooting Crocodiles\nBefore reaching Bali, we\nstopped at the most unspoiled\nisland we had seen Alor\nwhich was a part of the\nPITTSBURGH In ac\ncordance with the By-Laws of\nthe American Croatian Sing\nel's Federation we are calling\na conference of all the sing\ning societies affiliated with\nthe Federation.\nThis year the conference\nwill be held Saturday and\nSunday, March 22 and 23,\nin the Croatian National\nHome, Javor, 822 N. Canal\nStreet, Pittsburgh 12.\nEvery singing society has\nthe right to send 4 delegates\nto the conference, with the\ndelegate expenses to be paid\nTurn to page 8 for Editorial,\n'ACSF Conclave.\"\nby the society itself*. This rule\nalso applies in the cases of\nAlliance groups.\nOfficers of the Singers Fed\neration are authorized to at\ntend the conference, with\ntheir expenses to be paid by\nThe Zlatko Balokovic Story\nisland Of Bali A\nParadise on Earth\nProximity Warning Indicator Patrols Skies\nAIR over the United\nStates may look empty\nmost of the time, but actually\nit is too crowded for safety.\nDanger of aircraft collision\nlies not only over cities and\nairports, but above open\ncountry everywhere and, sur\nprisingly, it is just as great\non clear days as on cloudy\nnights.\nJBP -v -v\u2014\nLORD BLEDISLOE, center foreground, and Mr. and Mrs.\nZlatko Balokovic. at his right, posed for this picture during\nMr. Balokovic's concert visit in the early 1939's to New Zealand.\nThe Governor General of New ZeaJnnd at the time, Lord Blcd\nisloe, the Balokovics and members of the Governor's official\nstaff posed for the photo following a reception in honor of Mr.\nand Mrs. Balokovic at the Governor's House in Wellington,\nNew Zealand.\nDutch East Indies Archipela\ngo\u00ab\nThe natives of this island\nseemed extraordinarily primi\ntive to us.\nTheir heads were covered\nwith hair standing vertically\nto a height of almost a foot,\ntheir front teeth were filed to\na point, and since they all\nchewed betelnut, which is\nbright red, one had the im\npression that they had wash\ned their mouths in blood.\nHowever, we rapidly\nmade friends with them,\nand, as was our custom, di\nvided among the children\nFetc To Highlite Two-Pay Confab In Javor Hall\nSingers Federation Will Hold Conference In Pittsburgh\nthe Federation.\nAll delegates in attendance\nwill have equal rights to run\nfor positions as officers of the\nFederation and to take part\nin any other evfents.\nThe conference will con\nvene at approximately 11\na.m., Saturday, continue\nuntil 5:00 p.m., and open\nagain sometime the next\nday. We will adjourn Sun\nday afternoon, so as to\nmake it more convenient\nfor the delegates to return\nhome.\nWe ask all those delegates\nwho will attend the confer\u00ad\nAnswer To Plane Collisions\nTHE\nv i\nThe worst air catastro\nphe in our history occurred\non a bright sunny day a\nbout 21,000 feet above\ndesert.\nOn June 30, 1956, two pas\nsenger planes that had left\nLos Angeles more than an\nhour previously collided in\nmid-air over the Grand Can\nyon and crashed in the deso\nlate wastes of Arizona.\nAll on board, 128 men, wo\nmen and children, were killed.\nHuman Eye Can Fail\nWhat alarms pilots and av\niation officials mo6t is the\nnumber of near misses col\nlisions averted at the last\nsecond that are bei$g re-\ntoys and candies which we\nhad brought with us.\nWhen they told us through\nan interpreter that there were\ncrocodiles in the vicinity, we\nwent hunting. Almost imme\ndiately we spotted one with\nits head just above the tur\ngid waters of the tropical ri\nver and I was lucky enough\nto get him right in the eye\nfrom a distance of 65 yards.\nAs the crocodile was\nyards long, his skin was ideal\nfor handbags and, on arrival\nin Sourabaya-Java, I ordered\n(Life Story P. 11)\nence to send their names to\nthe undersigned and state\nwhether or not they will want\na hotel room. Reservations\nwTill then be made here and\nwe will notify you of the\nname of the hotel.\nThe Federation is contem\nplating a banquet, which\nwould be held Saturday eve\nning, March 22, in Javor Hall.\nThis would be accompanied by\na short musical program,\nwhich would be given by a\nfew of the district societies,\nand admission would be very\nnominal.\nThe Croatian Fraternal\nU n i o n S u e e o a\nMembers would also be in\nvited, as they will\" be\nholding their semi-annual\nsessions at that time.\nMore information, concern\ning the banquet, will appear\nlater.\nSteve Lipanovich, Sec'y.\nHOW PROXIMITY Warning Indicator works. Infrared rays\nfrom a small device on the plane \"see\" heat of engines or other\nparts of approaching planes and show their relative position\nto the pilot on a dial in the cockpit in time for 1dm to avoid\ntragic collision.\nported with increasing fre\nquency.\nThe fact is that the human\neye, especially after an hour\nor two of peering, is far from\nbeing the best instrument for\nscanning the heavens.\nThat is the reason a de\nvice that uses the infrared\nrays, invisible to the eye,\nfor locating nearby aircraft\nnow is uadergriog teste in\nCalifornia.\nMade by the Aerojet-Gen\neral Corporation at Azusa,\nnear Los Angeles, the instru\nment is called the Proximity\nWarning Indicator, abbrevi\nated to PWI.\nUse Spinning Mirror\nThe PWI is small. It\nweighs only about 30 pounds.\n(New Device P. 11).\nFebruary 19,1958\nHorsing\nMf\nAround\nWith The Editor -J\nTo prove that we don't\nknow everything, we learned\nfor the first time last week\nthat Feb. 10 is traditionally\nthe coldest day in Pitts\nburgh's weather annals.\nJust to make it look good,\nthe temperature here Feb. 10,\n1958, was one above zero.\nStill The Truth\nLabor disgraces no man\nunfortunate!^. you occasion-\nally find men disgrcicc labor.\nPres. U. S. Grant\nFrom 1877 Address\nBusiness Outlook\nAccording to the Amer\u00ad\nican Bankers Association, A\nmerica's most favorably situ\nated industries a\u00bb*e office\nequipment, electrical manu\nfacturing, electrical utility,\nand life insurance.,\nBuilt To Last\nOf the 2 million Cadillacs\nwhich have been produced ill\nthe 58-year-old history of the\ncompany, more than 50c of\nthose cars are still operating\non the highways of today a\nremarkable record in the au\ntomotive history of the Uni\nted States.\nLourdes Centenary\nMore than 6 million peo\nple from all parts of the world\nare expected to visit Lourdes,\nFrance, this year to help com\nmemorate the centenary of\nthis world famous center, the\nmost important holy site next\nto Rome for members of the\nRoman Catholic Church.\nTo Burn\nAmerica's tee-vee net\u00ad\nworks and independent sta\ntions will spend between $15\nand $20 millions on newspa\nper and magazine advertising\nin 1858, an all-time high.\nWays and Means\nSometimes a girl who\ndislikes a fellow's ways mar\nries him for his means.\nWorcester Telegram\nGood Old Uncle\nCongressional hearings\nare being conducted on biffs\nfor the building of two U.S.A.\nsuper-liners to enter the fab\nulous Atlantic and Pacific\npassenger trade.\nOne ship is estimated t#\ncost a cool $110 million, th\u00a7\nother a rather \"conservative1*\n$73 million. Government sub\nsidy would amount to about,\n45% on each ship.\nThink This Over\nFrom \"The Art of World\nly Wisdom,\" 1647: \"Once hate\nhas taken root it is, like bad\nrepute, difficult to eradicate.\"\nLighter Side\nThey tell the one about\nthe landlord who, asked whsf\nhe didn't light up the darjl\nhallway, replied:\n\"We had a light there for\n3 years. No one fell, so we\ntook it away.\"\nIrish Croatia\u00ab\nWas St. Patrick, the Pa*\ntron Saint of Erin, really a\ntrue-blue Irishman?\nWell, he came by way of\nDalmatia to go about the\nbusiness of becoming the\nmost beloved personage in the\nhistory of Ireland.\nAnd Dalmatia never was an\noufepoet of Eire!\nHow About That\nThe do-it-yourself move\nment might be carried far\nenough to include thinking\nthat way.\nThe Boston Globe\nFamous Last Words\nSenator William Langeff\n\"I'm just a poor farm 06\u00bb\nfrona North Dakota.\"","height":"25029","width":"19059"}}
